              <span id="reviewTextContainer587771409" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18317441086358779130">Because I love the four-corners region of the country, and because I relate to many aspects of some the Native American cultures who inhabited the region historically, and those who remain today, I wanted to read another Tony Hillerman novel. The only other I’ve read was long ago and far away; it’s not even listed among my Books Read list because I can remember nothing about it except that I liked it reasonably well. The Shape Shifter is #18 in his Navajo Mysteries series, and the one I read yea</span>
  <span id="freeText18317441086358779130" style="display:none">Because I love the four-corners region of the country, and because I relate to many aspects of some the Native American cultures who inhabited the region historically, and those who remain today, I wanted to read another Tony Hillerman novel. The only other I’ve read was long ago and far away; it’s not even listed among my Books Read list because I can remember nothing about it except that I liked it reasonably well. The Shape Shifter is #18 in his Navajo Mysteries series, and the one I read years back must have been among the first to feature Joe Leaphorn, a character I enjoy. Hillerman had quite a successful run with his protagonist, often referred to as the legendary Lieutenant Joe Leaphorn of the Navaho Tribal Nation Police, now retired. The fact that he has retired is a blessing, because he makes some dubious decisions in this tale that might just as easily ended with Joe dead on the ground, decisions that I believed a real-life detective would not have made. Lt. Joe Leaphorn dying is not something I ever want to read. He’s the kind of man I would want as a partner in a patrol car, the kind of man I would want to work for, a man to esteem. That said, the mystery of an antique rug—believed to have been destroyed in a suspicious fire years ago, when Joe’s law enforcement career was just beginning—a taletellers weaving that shows up on a wall in an upscale house in Flagstaff, is at least entertaining. The rug documents a period of great sadness for the Navajo people, an evil period that should never have been recorded for posterity, and as such in violation of Navajo beliefs. Instead, enemies are to be forgiven. Following the old ways, the Navajo Nation should carry on without carrying the baggage of revenge in their hearts. They know what they can expect from the white man. <br /> <br />The mystery is interesting and well-told, and includes nefarious CIA involvement during that infamously shady period of our misadventures in Southeast Asia, while hinting at paranormal elements inherent in a belief in the Skinwalkers and Shape Shifters found within Navajo witchcraft. <br /><br />Was the fire arson? Is it the handiwork of an ex-CIA operative or a modern-day Shape Shifter at the root of a series of robberies, and leaving a trail of dead victims? Is the same man responsible for a pattern of deceit among fellow thieves while he scoots away scot-free to steal invaluable artifacts and perpetuate insurance fraud? This light and diverting tale of little significance has enough suspense and violence to qualify for membership in the genre, but IMHO, the greatest appeal of The Shape Shifter, is found among diehard fans of Hillerman’s Navajo Mysteries. While it’s an enjoyable way to pass a few hours of time, I wanted to like it more than I do. With half-star ratings, this one would fall to two and-a-half.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18317441086358779130" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

