    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_63744805" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/63744805" />
    <a title="TBML" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2339196-tbml"><img alt="TBML" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1242850741p2/2339196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/63744805?book_show_action=true">Jul 16, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TBML" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TBML" href="/user/show/2339196-tbml">TBML</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer63744805&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer63744805" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1405661582252114008">This book was the Branigan BookClub August 2007 selection.<br/><br/>Picking my favorite Tony Hillerman book would be just as hard for me as it would be to find the perfect green chile cheeseburger. I have never read one of his books that I disliked, nor have I ever met a green chile cheeseburger that I didn&apos;t like! I have yet to find the perfect green chile cheeseburger, as there are so many eateries in NM that make them, and to date I haven&apos;t tried all of them. But I&apos;m doing my level best to rectify that</span>
  <span id="freeText1405661582252114008" style="display:none">This book was the Branigan BookClub August 2007 selection.<br /><br />Picking my favorite Tony Hillerman book would be just as hard for me as it would be to find the perfect green chile cheeseburger. I have never read one of his books that I disliked, nor have I ever met a green chile cheeseburger that I didn't like! I have yet to find the perfect green chile cheeseburger, as there are so many eateries in NM that make them, and to date I haven't tried all of them. But I'm doing my level best to rectify that regretable deficiency!<br /><br /><i>
  <b>The Shape Shifter</b>
</i>, however, is my favorite Hillerman book. It contains the most fully developed, mature and complex portrait of Leaphorn of any of the 18 Navajo Mysteries. The way Hillerman has him answer Jim Chee's question at the end about what happened to Delos has an apt symmetry and playful irony to it that is absolutely perfect. And the Legendary Lieutenant's answer to Bernie about his first case, Grandma Peshlakai's pinyon sap and tying up that case's loose ends is, if possible, even more perfect! They just don't get much better than this! <br /><br />Here's what happens in the book. Leaphorn is retired and to be honest, more than a little bored. Jim and Bernie are off on their honeymoon. A priceless Navajo rug that was involved in Joe's very first case as an officer in the Navajo Tribal Police, and that was destroyed in a fire, resurfaces and his interest is piqued. Soon after he starts to nose around to find out more, an acquaintance is killed in suspicious circumstances. Then, his life is threatened. Without Jim and Bernie to help him he must find out why people who ask about that rug are dying and who is responsible. In doing so, he opens up old cold cases and almost loses his own life. In the end, though, harmony is restored and he solves the cases. I know I sort of gave away the finale with that last sentence, but only in the most general sense, though. There are still more than enough twists and turns in the plot to keep you glued to your chair while you read this gem of a book! <br /><br />In <i>
  <b>The Shape Shifter</b>
</i>, Hillerman's readers will find the work of a master at the top of his form. Once again, we can relish his signature use of the land and skyscape of New Mexico as one of the main characters in his books. Once more we can appreciate his superbly honed skill as a story teller. One more time we can enjoy Leaphorn's company and marvel at his reasoning powers.<br /><br />--Mark Pendleton<br />Click <a href="http://chile.las-cruces.org/search?/tshape+shifter/tshape+shifter/1%2C2%2C4%2CB/exact&amp;FF=tshape+shifter&amp;1%2C3%2C/indexsort=-" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a> to find it in our library.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1405661582252114008" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


